WEBVTT

00:00:01.084 --> 00:00:05.300
- We're seeing big changes in the Dreams,
- Yes.

00:00:05.300 --> 00:00:07.692
thanks to their new GM, Sakurazaki.

00:00:07.692 --> 00:00:11.033
Yes. Not only did they trade for Sawada,

00:00:11.033 --> 00:00:13.742
but they surprised us all with Lim Min Jong.

00:00:13.742 --> 00:00:16.910
Sakurazaki is truly proving his worth.

00:00:16.910 --> 00:00:21.206
The Dreams may very well qualify
for the Climax Series this year.

00:00:21.206 --> 00:00:23.031
- I see.
- I'm home.

00:00:23.031 --> 00:00:27.242
However, others suspect
their team's offense has taken a hit

00:00:27.242 --> 00:00:30.679
after trading away their best hitter.

00:00:30.679 --> 00:00:34.337
- The hole left by Kudo is a large one.
- Right.

00:00:34.337 --> 00:00:37.245
But the Dreams have plenty of young athletes.

00:00:37.245 --> 00:00:40.001
- I'm home.
- They'll find someone.

00:00:40.001 --> 00:00:41.771
Welcome back.

00:00:41.771 --> 00:00:43.478
Have you eaten yet?

00:00:43.478 --> 00:00:45.613
Not yet. Thanks.

00:00:45.613 --> 00:00:46.775
Sure. (Support Admin Watch on kissasia.cam or kisskh.org)

00:01:16.846 --> 00:01:18.342
What?

00:01:20.926 --> 00:01:22.300
Jun?

00:01:25.129 --> 00:01:28.330
Your accountant exam is next week, right?

00:01:28.330 --> 00:01:30.018
Oh...

00:01:30.018 --> 00:01:31.080
Yeah.

00:01:33.925 --> 00:01:35.848
You feel ready for it?

00:01:37.104 --> 00:01:38.968
I guess.

00:01:41.529 --> 00:01:42.981
Study hard.

00:01:44.341 --> 00:01:46.221
Don't overdo it.

00:01:46.221 --> 00:01:47.800
I'm getting mixed messages.

00:01:49.708 --> 00:01:51.149
Great work, you all.

00:01:51.149 --> 00:01:52.229
Thank you, sir.

00:01:52.229 --> 00:01:54.460
- If you'll excuse us.
- Sure.

00:01:54.460 --> 00:01:58.409
Isami.

00:01:58.409 --> 00:01:59.660
Sir.

00:01:59.660 --> 00:02:04.729
I scroll tirelessly every day
to check on my company's reputation.

00:02:04.729 --> 00:02:06.806
So what's going on here?

00:02:06.806 --> 00:02:08.815
Explain it to me!

00:02:08.815 --> 00:02:10.358
Sir.

00:02:10.358 --> 00:02:12.319
This would be...

00:02:12.319 --> 00:02:14.047
The Dreams!

00:02:14.047 --> 00:02:16.611
They're making headlines!

00:02:17.652 --> 00:02:22.120
We can't have that happen. Absolutely not!

00:02:22.120 --> 00:02:23.204
I'm terribly sorry, sir.

00:02:23.204 --> 00:02:25.721
This team rakes in no money.

00:02:25.721 --> 00:02:28.664
So what's with all the attention? Huh?

00:02:28.664 --> 00:02:33.040
The GM may be acting out now,
but our plan remains unchanged.

00:02:33.040 --> 00:02:36.447
All will go as you wish, sir.

00:02:36.447 --> 00:02:38.119
So we can crush them?

00:02:38.119 --> 00:02:40.513
We can disband the team?

00:02:42.490 --> 00:02:44.340
I am working towards that goal.

00:02:44.340 --> 00:02:49.542
But sir, the dissolution of a team
is unprecedented in Japanese baseball.

00:02:49.542 --> 00:02:50.982
Unprecedented?

00:02:50.982 --> 00:02:54.173
I've spent my whole life
doing the unprecedented.

00:02:54.173 --> 00:02:55.661
That is why I'm a success.

00:02:55.661 --> 00:02:58.540
That is why Yaoshima exists. Am I wrong?

00:02:58.540 --> 00:02:59.856
No, sir.

00:02:59.856 --> 00:03:03.008
You're a capable man, aren't you?

00:03:03.008 --> 00:03:05.331
Well? Aren't you?

00:03:05.331 --> 00:03:06.542
Yes, sir.

00:03:06.542 --> 00:03:08.406
Of course you are.

00:03:12.971 --> 00:03:16.475
We're a family.

00:03:19.557 --> 00:03:21.114
A family, I say!

00:03:23.264 --> 00:03:25.433
You know what that means, right?

00:03:28.300 --> 00:03:30.565
But of course.

00:03:30.565 --> 00:03:32.471
- Mr. Mitsuo, it's time.
- What?

00:03:32.471 --> 00:03:34.217
It's almost time!

00:03:34.217 --> 00:03:37.504
- For what?
- For your dinner, sir!

00:03:42.283 --> 00:03:43.680
Oh, you.

00:03:54.396 --> 00:03:59.220
Maybe they'll find themselves victorious.

00:03:59.220 --> 00:04:01.152
They are dreamers, after all.

00:04:02.054 --> 00:04:03.804
Oh?

00:04:03.804 --> 00:04:05.681
What's with that face?

00:04:06.561 --> 00:04:09.037
Oh, right.

00:04:09.037 --> 00:04:14.328
Pops was singing praises about you.

00:04:14.328 --> 00:04:18.039
He said you turned out better
than your failure of a father.

00:04:19.938 --> 00:04:22.948
Don't be so angry.

00:04:22.948 --> 00:04:26.168
Nothing good comes out of arguing with me.

00:04:26.168 --> 00:04:30.360
We're cousins. Let's get along, yeah?

00:04:31.616 --> 00:04:35.845
I'm going to be
the face of this group someday.

00:04:35.845 --> 00:04:37.734
In other words,

00:04:37.734 --> 00:04:41.400
you'll become my right
or my left arm, at best.

00:04:41.400 --> 00:04:43.391
Let's go out to eat sometime.

00:04:43.391 --> 00:04:45.518
I'll treat you.

00:04:56.440 --> 00:04:58.276
See you later.

00:05:05.422 --> 00:05:06.922
Good morning.

00:05:06.922 --> 00:05:08.765
- Good morning.
- Morning.

00:05:09.638 --> 00:05:10.992
GM!

00:05:10.992 --> 00:05:13.156
I had the weekly "Baseball Continent"

00:05:13.156 --> 00:05:15.163
cover our draft and trade extensively.

00:05:15.163 --> 00:05:17.350
- Did you give it a watch?
- Yes.

00:05:17.350 --> 00:05:19.144
That program's an influential one.

00:05:19.144 --> 00:05:21.302
Baseball fans flock towards their coverage.

00:05:21.302 --> 00:05:24.508
Not to mention
their cohost is an absolute cutie.

00:05:24.508 --> 00:05:26.313
That's why you favor that program?

00:05:26.313 --> 00:05:27.941
I'm disillusioned.

00:05:27.941 --> 00:05:30.150
What? It's just my opinion!

00:05:30.150 --> 00:05:31.443
Don't worry.

00:05:31.443 --> 00:05:33.354
You two are cuties, too.

00:05:33.354 --> 00:05:34.354
- Creep.
- Creep.

00:05:34.354 --> 00:05:36.825
What? Surely that was the right thing to say.

00:05:36.825 --> 00:05:38.028
Right?

00:05:38.028 --> 00:05:39.829
- Creep!
- Creep!

00:05:39.829 --> 00:05:42.719
- Boom chika wow wow!
- Alright, I get it.

00:05:42.719 --> 00:05:44.113
- Creeps.
- Yeah!

00:05:44.113 --> 00:05:47.051
How are we tackling
the articles criticizing Lim?

00:05:47.051 --> 00:05:48.159
Pardon?

00:05:48.159 --> 00:05:50.182
Signing on to a Japanese team
instead of a Korean one

00:05:50.182 --> 00:05:53.063
seems to have caused a bit of backlash.

00:05:53.063 --> 00:05:55.479
Min Jong is still young.

00:05:55.479 --> 00:05:57.718
I'm worried the criticism
will cause him mental strain.

00:06:00.000 --> 00:06:01.859
[A traitor who sold his soul to Japan]

00:06:01.859 --> 00:06:03.694
This is terrible.

00:06:04.867 --> 00:06:06.303
We'll deal with it immediately.

00:06:06.303 --> 00:06:07.887
Thank you.

00:06:07.887 --> 00:06:10.181
The data needed
for annual salary negotiations

00:06:10.181 --> 00:06:12.563
will be ready within the week, Ms. President.

00:06:12.563 --> 00:06:14.657
Thank you.

00:06:14.657 --> 00:06:17.703
Another year, another difficult negotiation.

00:06:17.703 --> 00:06:19.107
Why is that?

00:06:19.107 --> 00:06:21.758
Management believes
the players are money sinks.

00:06:21.758 --> 00:06:24.214
They get stingy when discussing salaries.

00:06:24.214 --> 00:06:26.288
This is going to be tough.

00:06:26.288 --> 00:06:28.800
Even so, we manage to reach
an agreement every year.

00:06:28.800 --> 00:06:30.108
GM!

00:06:30.108 --> 00:06:32.043
Worry not, we've got this.

00:06:32.043 --> 00:06:33.717
You could stand to worry more.

00:06:33.717 --> 00:06:35.375
Ouch! Whoa!

00:06:35.375 --> 00:06:37.665
- Aw, my perfect hairdo...
- What hairdo?

00:06:37.665 --> 00:06:40.118
GM, I have bad news to add.

00:06:40.118 --> 00:06:42.798
Our data analyst, Mikami,
has decided to resign.

00:06:42.798 --> 00:06:44.948
What? He was one of our best.

00:06:44.948 --> 00:06:47.159
He's taking over his parents' tangerine farm.

00:06:47.159 --> 00:06:49.512
Gosh, they all quit so soon.

00:06:49.512 --> 00:06:51.976
Aren't you being too hard
on your subordinates?

00:06:51.976 --> 00:06:53.853
I'm totally fine.

00:06:53.853 --> 00:06:56.992
My boss is a bit punchy, but I'll manage.

00:06:56.992 --> 00:06:59.090
You're asking for another hit.

00:06:59.090 --> 00:07:00.457
No, no, I'm good. I'm good.

00:07:00.457 --> 00:07:04.623
I'll look for a former pro
who can replace Mikami.

00:07:04.623 --> 00:07:06.963
How about we do an open recruitment instead?

00:07:06.963 --> 00:07:08.571
Open recruitment?

00:07:08.571 --> 00:07:10.403
The job primarily deals with numbers.

00:07:10.403 --> 00:07:12.050
We should expand past former pros,

00:07:12.050 --> 00:07:14.060
and consider hiring statisticians as well.

00:07:14.802 --> 00:07:17.111
Have you heard of "Banzai Baseball"?

00:07:17.111 --> 00:07:18.845
It's a blog run by an ordinary fan,

00:07:18.845 --> 00:07:21.039
who posts about highly analytical topics.

00:07:21.039 --> 00:07:24.943
If you're not a former player,
then you can't fully understand the stats.

00:07:24.943 --> 00:07:28.129
We haven't even implemented Sabermetrics.
[T/N: the empirical analysis of baseball]

00:07:28.129 --> 00:07:30.720
There's no harm in speaking
to an analytical expert.

00:07:30.720 --> 00:07:34.477
I can't work with people
who don't know baseball.

00:07:35.454 --> 00:07:38.787
Knowledgeable or not,
there are capable individuals out there.

00:07:40.491 --> 00:07:44.734
I, too, have no experience with baseball.

00:07:47.408 --> 00:07:49.054
He said it himself.

00:07:49.054 --> 00:07:51.436
He's throwing himself under the bus.

00:07:51.436 --> 00:07:53.357
What an inspirational act of self sacrifice.

00:07:53.357 --> 00:07:57.091
I've never been more moved in my life.

00:07:57.091 --> 00:07:58.696
Anyone agree?

00:07:59.411 --> 00:08:03.547
He sure is the Prince of Nonchalance, huh?

00:08:03.547 --> 00:08:06.476
Not all big league coaches
used to be players.

00:08:06.476 --> 00:08:10.495
Even the Pelicans have a statistician
lead their data analytics team.

00:08:10.495 --> 00:08:12.474
In baseball,

00:08:12.474 --> 00:08:16.287
only those with experience
can give an accurate analysis.

00:08:16.287 --> 00:08:20.036
Why has every day felt so prickly lately?

00:08:20.036 --> 00:08:22.185
Let's advocate for peace.

00:08:22.185 --> 00:08:26.558
Do you know why I start my mornings
at the batting range?

00:08:26.558 --> 00:08:27.993
No.

00:08:27.993 --> 00:08:30.529
It's so the players don't underestimate me.

00:08:31.365 --> 00:08:34.784
They are all confident in their abilities.

00:08:34.784 --> 00:08:37.503
No matter how correct the analysis is,

00:08:37.503 --> 00:08:41.406
they will not listen to the advice
of an inexperienced person.

00:08:43.166 --> 00:08:44.845
Experienced or not,

00:08:44.845 --> 00:08:48.524
players will listen,
if they're thoroughly convinced.

00:08:48.524 --> 00:08:51.588
But these athletes know only of baseball.

00:08:51.588 --> 00:08:55.657
Correct the wrongs of your players
before focusing on your own body.

00:08:58.183 --> 00:09:02.759
We'll invite both specialists
and former professionals alike to apply.

00:09:03.689 --> 00:09:04.694
Yes, sir.

00:09:04.694 --> 00:09:08.446
That's all for now.
Let's start our morning assembly.

00:09:14.962 --> 00:09:16.778
First on the docket.

00:09:52.399 --> 00:09:56.390
Miyahara, our analytics team got back to us.

00:10:05.426 --> 00:10:07.178
Yes?

00:10:07.178 --> 00:10:09.989
You call on Miyahara often these days.

00:10:09.989 --> 00:10:12.698
Certainly not by choice.

00:10:12.698 --> 00:10:17.357
You used to get on his case
for getting in with connections.

00:10:19.317 --> 00:10:22.563
Where did that anger go, I wonder?

00:10:25.932 --> 00:10:27.726
[FY2023 New Hire Interview Room]

00:10:34.463 --> 00:10:36.942
Miyahara's up next, huh?

00:10:36.942 --> 00:10:39.707
The youngest son from the Aiba Corporation?

00:10:39.707 --> 00:10:41.172
Yeah.

00:10:41.172 --> 00:10:44.294
I owe a lot to his father.

00:10:44.294 --> 00:10:45.451
Likewise.

00:10:47.526 --> 00:10:49.035
Excuse me.

00:10:50.371 --> 00:10:52.079
Mr. Miyahara.

00:11:00.886 --> 00:11:02.656
Mr. Miyahara.

00:11:05.134 --> 00:11:06.752
Mr. Miyahara!

00:11:06.752 --> 00:11:09.019
Woah! You startled me.

00:11:09.019 --> 00:11:11.034
It's your turn. Please stand.

00:11:11.034 --> 00:11:12.346
Hello.

00:11:12.346 --> 00:11:14.130
- Huh?
- Hurry up!

00:11:14.130 --> 00:11:16.521
- Yes...
- You're making everyone wait.

00:11:16.521 --> 00:11:18.132
Huh? What year is it?

00:11:18.132 --> 00:11:19.408
Itsuki Miyahara?

00:11:19.408 --> 00:11:20.646
Yes, sir!

00:11:20.646 --> 00:11:23.859
First, let's hear a bit more about you.

00:11:23.859 --> 00:11:24.749
Yes, sir!

00:11:24.749 --> 00:11:27.262
Just know I'll do anything!

00:11:27.262 --> 00:11:29.280
I'll work super, duper hard!

00:11:29.280 --> 00:11:32.745
I'm ready to put my whole back into it!

00:11:32.745 --> 00:11:35.245
It's nice to see you're so energetic.

00:11:35.245 --> 00:11:38.236
Motivation and energy
are all I got going for me.

00:11:38.236 --> 00:11:41.149
Ask, and I, Itsuki Miyahara, will do it.

00:11:41.149 --> 00:11:44.716
Motivation plus energy, equals Miyahara.

00:11:44.716 --> 00:11:46.620
I love the Dreams! Go team!

00:11:46.620 --> 00:11:49.078
You're a real shining applicant, kid!

00:11:49.078 --> 00:11:50.154
Thank you very much.

00:11:50.154 --> 00:11:51.489
I also like the hairdo.

00:11:51.489 --> 00:11:53.357
You noticed? Thank you!

00:11:53.357 --> 00:11:54.583
Ow, ouch!

00:11:54.583 --> 00:11:57.135
Ouch, ouch!

00:11:57.135 --> 00:11:58.463
Ma'am, what the--

00:11:58.463 --> 00:11:59.400
Ow!

00:11:59.400 --> 00:12:00.462
Do you want to die?

00:12:00.462 --> 00:12:02.309
Wait a minute. What did I do?

00:12:02.309 --> 00:12:05.294
Do you understand how everyone else feels
about this interview?

00:12:05.294 --> 00:12:06.771
Please, wait. What are you...

00:12:06.771 --> 00:12:10.604
An earnest worker is going
to get rejected because of you.

00:12:12.655 --> 00:12:14.771
You've got connections.

00:12:14.771 --> 00:12:16.752
If you pass, don't bother coming in.

00:12:16.752 --> 00:12:19.274
I'll beat the living daylights out of you.

00:12:21.828 --> 00:12:24.620
What is with that lady?

00:12:32.368 --> 00:12:34.708
Miyahara has returned.

00:12:34.708 --> 00:12:35.984
- Welcome back.
- Thanks!

00:12:35.984 --> 00:12:37.307
Hey there, connections hire.

00:12:37.307 --> 00:12:38.861
What's all this about?

00:12:38.861 --> 00:12:42.389
Why did you answer?
I thought you "had no connections".

00:12:42.389 --> 00:12:44.812
Oops! Ouch!

00:12:44.812 --> 00:12:46.303
Please forgive me.

00:12:46.303 --> 00:12:47.787
Sorry, sorry.

00:12:47.787 --> 00:12:50.567
But you were rejected,
even with your connections.

00:12:50.567 --> 00:12:51.540
Why's that?

00:12:51.540 --> 00:12:54.449
I wasn't rejected. I withdrew.

00:12:54.449 --> 00:12:56.776
I decided not to rely on connections.

00:12:56.776 --> 00:12:59.855
The following year, I passed all on my own.

00:12:59.855 --> 00:13:01.754
Boom chika wow wow!

00:13:01.754 --> 00:13:03.920
- Surprised?
- Really? I had no idea.

00:13:03.920 --> 00:13:04.728
Yup.

00:13:04.728 --> 00:13:06.540
Because if I got in through connections,

00:13:06.540 --> 00:13:09.316
a certain someone promised she'd beat me up.

00:13:09.316 --> 00:13:11.760
Good going, Miyahara!

00:13:11.760 --> 00:13:13.114
Woah, hey!

00:13:13.114 --> 00:13:14.334
- You rich idiot!
- Hey!

00:13:14.334 --> 00:13:16.128
That's what you think of me?

00:13:16.128 --> 00:13:17.612
I mean, you're not entirely wrong, but...

00:13:17.612 --> 00:13:19.068
Good morning.

00:13:19.068 --> 00:13:21.497
- Good morning.
- Morning, sir.

00:13:21.497 --> 00:13:24.158
Have we received applications
for our data analyst position?

00:13:24.158 --> 00:13:25.286
Yes, about ten.

00:13:25.286 --> 00:13:28.213
Great. Then we'll hold interviews tomorrow.

00:13:28.213 --> 00:13:31.508
What? All ten of them, tomorrow?

00:13:31.508 --> 00:13:33.308
Why not?

00:13:33.308 --> 00:13:35.876
There are preparations to make, and...

00:13:35.876 --> 00:13:36.893
GM?

00:13:36.893 --> 00:13:39.255
The least you could do is listen to me!

00:13:39.255 --> 00:13:41.252
And he's gone.

00:13:42.899 --> 00:13:44.756
I'm home.

00:13:44.756 --> 00:13:46.309
Welcome back.

00:13:48.449 --> 00:13:51.477
It's tomorrow, right? Your accountant's exam.

00:13:52.371 --> 00:13:53.412
Yeah.

00:13:54.704 --> 00:13:56.938
I'm going to bed. Good night.

00:13:59.345 --> 00:14:00.943
Good night.

00:14:05.954 --> 00:14:07.085
Jun.

00:14:07.085 --> 00:14:09.073
What's up?

00:14:09.700 --> 00:14:11.578
I wanted to talk about baseball.

00:14:14.510 --> 00:14:16.475
Has it been fun?

00:14:18.737 --> 00:14:20.996
Yeah, it's fun.

00:14:20.996 --> 00:14:22.965
And I like playing, but...

00:14:25.943 --> 00:14:30.138
Maybe all the practice is making me unsure.

00:14:30.138 --> 00:14:32.182
I know I should like it.

00:14:32.182 --> 00:14:34.117
But it's starting to wear on me.

00:14:35.831 --> 00:14:37.767
Akito.

00:14:37.767 --> 00:14:40.816
You can't be whining like that.

00:14:44.161 --> 00:14:48.606
Concentrate on the goals in front of you.

00:14:50.933 --> 00:14:52.696
You're right.

00:14:52.696 --> 00:14:54.412
Do your best.

00:14:55.569 --> 00:14:56.915
Okay.

00:15:48.522 --> 00:15:51.550
We haven't even implemented Sabermetrics.

00:15:51.550 --> 00:15:54.115
Have you heard of "Banzai Baseball"?

00:16:00.438 --> 00:16:03.778
["Banzai Baseball", "Blog"]

00:16:07.713 --> 00:16:11.368
[Banzai Baseball]

00:16:11.368 --> 00:16:14.293
[Pitchers shouldn't play defense]

00:16:14.293 --> 00:16:16.383
[Writer - Robinson]

00:16:41.637 --> 00:16:43.643
Are you ready for the exam?

00:16:43.643 --> 00:16:45.232
Yeah.

00:16:49.455 --> 00:16:51.861
There's always the next year.

00:16:52.736 --> 00:16:54.837
Take it easy, alright?

00:16:54.837 --> 00:16:57.177
Don't worry, I'll pass.

00:17:01.946 --> 00:17:08.563
Then we'll use both our salaries
to move Mom closer to us.

00:17:13.457 --> 00:17:15.178
Thanks for breakfast.

00:17:22.514 --> 00:17:24.396
I'll be heading out first.

00:17:31.020 --> 00:17:32.767
Take a taxi to the exam.

00:17:47.863 --> 00:17:51.785
I'll call in the next applicant.

00:17:51.785 --> 00:17:53.381
Go ahead.

00:17:53.381 --> 00:17:56.262
It's kind of nerve-wracking,
having to choose people.

00:17:56.262 --> 00:17:58.757
Leave your thoughts for later. Call them in.

00:17:58.757 --> 00:17:59.999
Yes, ma'am!

00:18:00.947 --> 00:18:03.102
Come on in.

00:18:03.970 --> 00:18:06.413
You're currently studying sabermetrics?

00:18:06.413 --> 00:18:07.427
Yes.

00:18:07.427 --> 00:18:08.949
Then allow me to ask.

00:18:08.949 --> 00:18:12.709
What is the numerical metric
used to evaluate a pitcher's ability?

00:18:12.709 --> 00:18:16.031
A throw-to-strike ratio measured per inning.

00:18:16.031 --> 00:18:17.457
And why is that?

00:18:17.457 --> 00:18:18.826
In modern baseball,

00:18:18.826 --> 00:18:22.584
it is crucial to strike a batter out
with the least amount of pitches possible.

00:18:22.584 --> 00:18:25.418
So speed and type of pitch do not matter?

00:18:25.418 --> 00:18:28.544
A pitcher can throw a fastball,
or a disappearing fork,

00:18:28.544 --> 00:18:30.372
but it must be a strike.

00:18:30.372 --> 00:18:33.212
A steady pitch that consistently strikes out

00:18:33.212 --> 00:18:36.750
is far more appealing than anything flashy.

00:18:36.750 --> 00:18:40.990
But a professional batter
will easily get used to one type of pitch.

00:18:40.990 --> 00:18:42.558
Over the course of a long season,

00:18:42.558 --> 00:18:45.786
are you sure that metric alone will work?

00:18:47.785 --> 00:18:49.797
I do not know.

00:18:51.689 --> 00:18:54.445
I see. Thank you.

00:18:54.445 --> 00:18:57.155
Thank you, we'll be in touch.

00:18:58.955 --> 00:19:00.784
Great work, team.

00:19:00.784 --> 00:19:02.977
Prez, you really showed him your stuff.

00:19:02.977 --> 00:19:04.732
You think?

00:19:04.732 --> 00:19:07.625
What was the correct answer to that question?

00:19:07.625 --> 00:19:10.476
There was no correct answer.
I was testing his analytical skills.

00:19:10.476 --> 00:19:12.119
It was a trick question?

00:19:12.119 --> 00:19:14.130
You studied up on analytics?

00:19:14.130 --> 00:19:17.100
Yes. I referenced some books,
and "Banzai Baseball".

00:19:20.361 --> 00:19:22.505
Come on in.

00:19:31.532 --> 00:19:33.358
Excuse me.

00:19:37.103 --> 00:19:38.572
Huh?

00:19:40.974 --> 00:19:42.450
Oh.

00:19:43.733 --> 00:19:45.367
Are you alright?

00:19:45.367 --> 00:19:47.814
Yes, I'll handle it myself.

00:19:47.814 --> 00:19:49.843
Oh, okay.

00:19:57.111 --> 00:19:58.579
May I?

00:19:58.579 --> 00:20:01.124
- Thank you.
- Okay, here I go.

00:20:01.124 --> 00:20:02.855
Heave-ho.

00:20:04.100 --> 00:20:06.961
- Thank you.
- Of course.

00:20:06.961 --> 00:20:08.544
There we go.

00:20:12.523 --> 00:20:14.005
Thank you.

00:20:19.195 --> 00:20:21.351
Thank you for having me.

00:20:21.351 --> 00:20:23.825
Then let us begin.

00:20:25.653 --> 00:20:28.348
May I share some documents first?

00:20:29.537 --> 00:20:31.130
I'll pass them out.

00:20:31.130 --> 00:20:33.510
- Thank you.
- Sure thing.

00:20:33.510 --> 00:20:35.382
Alright.

00:20:35.382 --> 00:20:36.747
One for me.

00:20:37.432 --> 00:20:39.789
One for you.

00:20:39.789 --> 00:20:41.709
One for you.
[Pitchers shouldn't play defense]

00:20:41.709 --> 00:20:43.593
And you, sir.
[Heat changes the ball game]

00:20:45.577 --> 00:20:46.869
No way.

00:20:47.632 --> 00:20:50.718
Are you Robinson, of "Banzai Baseball"?

00:20:51.854 --> 00:20:53.689
Author of "Pitchers shouldn't play defense",

00:20:53.689 --> 00:20:56.558
and "AI Pitching Strategies"?

00:20:56.558 --> 00:20:58.383
Yes.

00:20:58.383 --> 00:20:59.902
What?

00:20:59.902 --> 00:21:01.386
Wow!

00:21:01.386 --> 00:21:02.974
You don't know him?

00:21:02.974 --> 00:21:04.453
No.

00:21:04.453 --> 00:21:06.566
He's a very famous writer.

00:21:06.566 --> 00:21:08.173
- Right?
- Yes.

00:21:09.063 --> 00:21:11.154
I'm Akito Sakurazaki.

00:21:12.391 --> 00:21:14.035
Today, I've brought you all summaries

00:21:14.035 --> 00:21:17.511
of articles I wrote regarding asset analysis.

00:21:17.511 --> 00:21:20.430
This is quite the stack.

00:21:20.430 --> 00:21:23.343
Your method of tracking a player's records

00:21:23.343 --> 00:21:25.882
is also considered a type of sabermetrics.

00:21:25.882 --> 00:21:28.003
It's simply a different interpretation of it.

00:21:28.003 --> 00:21:29.792
In baseball,

00:21:29.792 --> 00:21:33.481
many elements are not reflected in data.

00:21:33.481 --> 00:21:35.937
For example, a player in a slump

00:21:35.937 --> 00:21:40.037
could be suffering from heartbreak,
or a family issue.

00:21:40.037 --> 00:21:42.703
Can these factors be quantified?

00:21:42.703 --> 00:21:46.445
Baseball is the easiest sport
to numerically quantify.

00:21:47.340 --> 00:21:50.532
Basketball and soccer heavily rely on a team.

00:21:50.532 --> 00:21:54.600
But strikeouts and hits
are both done by a single player.

00:21:54.600 --> 00:21:56.819
Not implementing sabermetrics,

00:21:56.819 --> 00:21:59.960
is like a doctor telling you
he's not interested in your health.

00:21:59.960 --> 00:22:02.200
Sabermetrics is not
an official academic discipline.

00:22:02.200 --> 00:22:04.803
Yet if we do not propagate this study,

00:22:04.803 --> 00:22:07.743
it will greatly affect
the future of baseball.

00:22:07.743 --> 00:22:09.825
Jun.

00:22:09.825 --> 00:22:12.490
If I quit baseball,
will you teach me to study?

00:22:12.490 --> 00:22:14.603
You're not cut out for studying.

00:22:14.603 --> 00:22:16.512
Keep playing baseball.

00:22:17.190 --> 00:22:18.980
I have to get back to work.

00:22:18.980 --> 00:22:20.426
I have a game today.

00:22:20.426 --> 00:22:22.513
Then do your best.

00:22:24.776 --> 00:22:28.534
My pelvis has been hurting since yesterday.

00:22:28.534 --> 00:22:31.118
If you're afraid of pain, you'll slow down.

00:22:31.118 --> 00:22:33.763
Focus on what's in front, and run.

00:22:36.227 --> 00:22:37.847
Focus.

00:22:37.847 --> 00:22:39.985
Don't be afraid of pain. Do your best.

00:22:39.985 --> 00:22:41.879
The results will follow.

00:22:46.539 --> 00:22:49.679
I'll call back after the match. Good luck.

00:23:04.101 --> 00:23:06.466
The Titans, who are currently undefeated,

00:23:06.466 --> 00:23:09.457
have not yet implemented sabermetrics.

00:23:09.457 --> 00:23:12.070
That's a common misconception.

00:23:12.070 --> 00:23:14.194
Their analytic work
is outsourced to a sabermetrics expert.

00:23:14.194 --> 00:23:16.160
What? Seriously?

00:23:16.160 --> 00:23:20.323
Titans' analysts wish to remain contractors
because they are paid more this way.

00:23:20.323 --> 00:23:22.928
I get that you're good with numbers.

00:23:22.928 --> 00:23:26.081
But you have no experience on the field.

00:23:26.081 --> 00:23:28.134
Will you be able to survive on the team?

00:23:35.072 --> 00:23:37.376
I have experience playing baseball.

00:23:37.376 --> 00:23:38.979
Sandlot baseball?

00:23:39.927 --> 00:23:41.648
No, Koshien.

00:23:45.369 --> 00:23:47.774
If a more proficient
sabermetrics expert has applied,

00:23:47.774 --> 00:23:51.309
I suggest hiring them,
even if they're a baseball amateur.

00:23:51.309 --> 00:23:53.107
He's so reliable.

00:23:53.107 --> 00:23:57.600
Wow, I can practically taste victory already!

00:23:57.600 --> 00:24:01.005
Sabermetrics alone won't change the rankings.

00:24:01.005 --> 00:24:05.197
However, incorporating statistical analysis
will expand this team's possibilities.

00:24:05.197 --> 00:24:08.107
What do you think of the sacrifice bunt?

00:24:10.374 --> 00:24:13.654
You're asking so many questions, Mr. Inamura.

00:24:13.654 --> 00:24:17.101
According to sabermetrics,
the sacrifice bunt is considered irrational,

00:24:17.101 --> 00:24:20.026
yet it is still used in the Japanese league.

00:24:20.026 --> 00:24:22.609
What are your thoughts on this?

00:24:22.609 --> 00:24:25.814
An out reduces the chance for scoring.

00:24:25.814 --> 00:24:29.899
If victory is the priority,
a sacrifice bunt is clearly ineffective.

00:24:30.808 --> 00:24:35.077
However, data analysis is like cooking.

00:24:35.077 --> 00:24:37.040
Data is like an ingredient.

00:24:37.040 --> 00:24:41.279
It's up to the analyst to use
those ingredients in a meaningful manner.

00:24:41.279 --> 00:24:46.914
Teams may have a need for bunts,
depending on their strengths or weaknesses.

00:24:46.914 --> 00:24:49.199
I can't rule them out entirely.

00:24:49.914 --> 00:24:52.750
What would you do?

00:24:52.750 --> 00:24:55.176
I've heard that
the Dreams are aiming to win the series.

00:24:55.176 --> 00:24:57.982
In that case,
I would forgo sacrifice bunts entirely

00:24:57.982 --> 00:25:00.743
to further improve our chances at victory.

00:25:03.416 --> 00:25:05.038
Any other questions?

00:25:05.038 --> 00:25:07.658
No, none.

00:25:07.658 --> 00:25:09.329
GM?

00:25:10.041 --> 00:25:12.113
How many centimeters was that?

00:25:17.100 --> 00:25:18.913
When you entered this room,

00:25:18.913 --> 00:25:22.040
which you could not even overcome alone?

00:25:27.073 --> 00:25:29.089
It's about 5 centimeters tall.

00:25:29.089 --> 00:25:32.496
Your work will be more difficult
than overcoming a 5 centimeter hump.

00:25:32.496 --> 00:25:33.759
GM!

00:25:33.759 --> 00:25:35.937
I'm simply telling him the truth.

00:25:40.005 --> 00:25:44.145
I like Jackie Robinson.
Hence my pen name online.

00:25:45.876 --> 00:25:49.449
The referees were always making decisions
against Jackie Robinson.

00:25:49.449 --> 00:25:51.569
There were a lot of dead balls.

00:25:52.338 --> 00:25:54.823
Because he was African-American.

00:25:57.391 --> 00:26:00.382
But he never gave in
to that sort of adversity.

00:26:01.812 --> 00:26:03.671
I won't either.

00:26:05.724 --> 00:26:08.347
- Can I ask you one more question?
- What caused your injury?

00:26:19.899 --> 00:26:21.523
The cause was...

00:27:01.156 --> 00:27:03.533
Don't be afraid of pain. Do your best.

00:27:06.596 --> 00:27:09.123
Focus on what's in front, and run.

00:27:12.379 --> 00:27:16.861
Concentrate on the goals in front of you.

00:27:40.738 --> 00:27:43.019
Time out! Are you okay?

00:27:43.656 --> 00:27:45.612
Stretcher!

00:27:46.337 --> 00:27:48.497
I was injured during a match.

00:27:54.472 --> 00:27:59.292
An analyst watches tons of game footage.

00:28:00.654 --> 00:28:05.919
You'll be reminded of your past
every time you watch a match.

00:28:05.919 --> 00:28:08.364
Can you bear those painful memories?

00:28:09.528 --> 00:28:10.630
I'll be fine.

00:28:10.630 --> 00:28:14.968
Will your family allow you to work here?

00:28:15.646 --> 00:28:17.831
I wouldn't know.

00:28:17.831 --> 00:28:19.963
But I'm okay.

00:28:19.963 --> 00:28:21.953
Because I love baseball.

00:28:40.380 --> 00:28:43.015
Akito Sakurazaki is my younger brother.

00:28:43.015 --> 00:28:44.387
I thought so!

00:28:44.387 --> 00:28:48.150
The same surname tipped me off.

00:28:48.150 --> 00:28:49.731
You have a spectacular brother.

00:28:49.731 --> 00:28:51.678
Please make your choice objectively.

00:28:51.678 --> 00:28:53.208
I will not be choosing him.

00:28:53.208 --> 00:28:55.318
Huh? Why?

00:28:55.318 --> 00:28:57.213
Do you make subjective judgements, GM?

00:28:57.213 --> 00:28:59.883
My brother knows I will turn him down.

00:28:59.883 --> 00:29:01.830
You didn't have to be so harsh on him.

00:29:01.830 --> 00:29:03.140
Yeah, GM.

00:29:03.140 --> 00:29:05.531
If it were me, I'd be left crushed.

00:29:05.531 --> 00:29:07.291
No one asked for your opinion.

00:29:07.291 --> 00:29:08.183
Ouch!

00:29:08.183 --> 00:29:10.051
Ouch! Twice?

00:29:10.891 --> 00:29:14.651
Fine. Let us make the decision ourselves.

00:29:14.651 --> 00:29:17.637
Huh? Are we allowed to decide without the GM?

00:29:17.637 --> 00:29:19.652
We'll have to.

00:29:20.700 --> 00:29:22.197
I don't get it.

00:29:22.197 --> 00:29:24.700
I don't get that GM.

00:29:24.700 --> 00:29:27.273
I just don't get him.

00:29:27.273 --> 00:29:30.405
Something's up.

00:29:30.405 --> 00:29:32.671
I know something's up. I know it.

00:29:32.671 --> 00:29:34.322
Something's fishy here.

00:29:34.322 --> 00:29:36.482
No, no. It's all too fishy.

00:29:36.482 --> 00:29:37.680
Risa.

00:29:37.680 --> 00:29:40.298
I get that you want me to ask what's up.

00:29:40.298 --> 00:29:43.213
But in that case,
I'd rather you be direct about it.

00:29:43.213 --> 00:29:44.380
Then ask me.

00:29:44.380 --> 00:29:45.595
Risa.

00:29:45.595 --> 00:29:48.415
This GM has made you all... strange.

00:29:48.415 --> 00:29:50.621
Exactly, our GM is acting strange.

00:29:51.409 --> 00:29:52.936
Are we on the same page here?

00:29:52.936 --> 00:29:55.095
He lost his usual cool demeanor.

00:29:55.095 --> 00:29:57.619
Is working with your sibling really so bad?

00:29:57.619 --> 00:29:58.608
Obviously.

00:29:58.608 --> 00:29:59.610
Why? Why? Why?

00:29:59.610 --> 00:30:01.284
Too close.

00:30:01.284 --> 00:30:05.060
See? If you're too close,
you'll lose sight of your surroundings.

00:30:05.060 --> 00:30:07.582
Who cares? I like being close.

00:30:07.582 --> 00:30:09.742
Really now.

00:30:10.411 --> 00:30:13.170
I wonder what reasons he could have?

00:30:14.252 --> 00:30:16.242
Well, for one, it'd get noisy.

00:30:16.242 --> 00:30:18.708
You'd also cling to me.

00:30:18.708 --> 00:30:21.084
Not to mention your potty-mouth...

00:30:21.084 --> 00:30:22.733
- Who are you talking about?
- Huh?

00:30:22.733 --> 00:30:23.748
- Huh?
- Huh?

00:30:23.748 --> 00:30:24.924
- The GM?
- Who?

00:30:24.924 --> 00:30:26.036
Huh?

00:30:28.784 --> 00:30:32.334
[Akito Sakurazaki]

00:30:41.263 --> 00:30:44.188
[The end to a promising baseball star]

00:30:44.188 --> 00:30:47.128
[Akito Sakurazaki]
[Injured while running to base]

00:31:01.233 --> 00:31:03.668
[Ignoring the pain led to severe injury]

00:31:03.668 --> 00:31:05.410
[Tragedy of a promising player]

00:31:05.410 --> 00:31:07.162
[Made it all the way to the baseball Koshien]

00:31:20.406 --> 00:31:21.940
GM!

00:31:24.029 --> 00:31:25.814
After thoroughly investigating our building,

00:31:25.814 --> 00:31:28.216
I found eight doors with a threshold
of two centimeters or less.

00:31:28.216 --> 00:31:30.182
Totally wheelchair accessible.

00:31:31.589 --> 00:31:34.277
We will also install ramps where necessary.

00:31:34.277 --> 00:31:36.572
It'd be cheaper
than replacing the doors themselves.

00:31:36.572 --> 00:31:38.607
That is none of my business.

00:31:42.066 --> 00:31:44.178
Excuse me?

00:31:48.569 --> 00:31:50.528
I'm coming in.

00:31:50.528 --> 00:31:53.658
- What are you doing?
- I'm not done yet.

00:31:59.696 --> 00:32:02.656
Your brother was a star player.

00:32:05.941 --> 00:32:07.778
It's all in the past now.

00:32:10.368 --> 00:32:12.597
Have you read this?
[Utilizing Sabermetrics - Akito Sakurazaki]

00:32:12.597 --> 00:32:14.869
Do you really understand?

00:32:14.869 --> 00:32:18.449
I do not feel comfortable
discussing my family with you.

00:32:18.449 --> 00:32:21.232
I'm here to talk about potential hires.

00:32:26.250 --> 00:32:28.482
Please take a good look at these documents.

00:32:30.608 --> 00:32:32.198
[Utilizing Sabermetrics - Akito Sakurazaki]

00:32:35.762 --> 00:32:40.236
I believe he overcame the pain,
and found his passion for baseball.

00:32:41.372 --> 00:32:44.139
That passion, brought him to us.

00:32:46.725 --> 00:32:47.577
Please get out.

00:32:47.577 --> 00:32:49.607
I understand your concerns.

00:32:49.607 --> 00:32:54.023
But, GM, why won't you recognize his efforts?

00:32:54.023 --> 00:32:56.636
This has nothing to do with the Dreams.

00:32:56.636 --> 00:32:58.193
I won't hire him because of mere connections.

00:32:58.193 --> 00:33:00.581
And we won't choose him
because you two are family.

00:33:01.546 --> 00:33:04.328
We will judge him
for his own brilliant abilities,

00:33:04.328 --> 00:33:08.306
and the results of his accumulated efforts.

00:33:11.580 --> 00:33:16.342
Even if there are doubts,
we've already hired a reliable...

00:33:16.342 --> 00:33:20.503
a stupidly honest rich kid working for us.

00:33:24.206 --> 00:33:28.962
In any case, please see him for who he is.

00:33:32.636 --> 00:33:34.423
Good night.

00:33:56.843 --> 00:33:59.238
[New waves brought on by Dreams' Sakurazaki]

00:33:59.238 --> 00:34:01.098
[Though he has no baseball experience...]

00:34:06.468 --> 00:34:07.899
Welcome back.

00:34:18.683 --> 00:34:20.720
How long have you been writing?

00:34:25.106 --> 00:34:26.959
A long time now.

00:34:28.141 --> 00:34:29.170
You've been lying to me?

00:34:29.170 --> 00:34:31.468
I never meant to hide it from you.

00:34:31.468 --> 00:34:33.580
I just like baseball.

00:34:34.959 --> 00:34:37.393
I wanted to make your life easier.

00:34:37.393 --> 00:34:40.614
When I played, it caused me nothing but pain.

00:34:40.614 --> 00:34:42.099
But now...

00:34:45.840 --> 00:34:48.437
I truly love baseball.

00:34:48.437 --> 00:34:49.566
I really do.

00:34:54.208 --> 00:34:56.906
I was going to tell you I moved on.

00:35:00.405 --> 00:35:02.944
Then why didn't you?

00:35:02.944 --> 00:35:05.895
You hated the sport.

00:35:05.895 --> 00:35:08.116
How could I tell you I loved it?

00:35:11.228 --> 00:35:12.855
That's because...

00:35:15.948 --> 00:35:17.238
Because baseball made you...

00:35:17.238 --> 00:35:18.759
No.

00:35:21.278 --> 00:35:25.232
Deep down, you blame yourself, don't you?

00:35:29.894 --> 00:35:32.108
But that happened years ago.

00:35:35.543 --> 00:35:40.398
How could a GM not show his brother
a single match of baseball?

00:35:41.670 --> 00:35:43.869
That's just strange.

00:35:45.954 --> 00:35:47.915
If you hate the sport so much,

00:35:49.176 --> 00:35:51.191
why work for a baseball team?

00:35:51.191 --> 00:35:53.103
Then who will put food on the table?

00:35:53.916 --> 00:35:55.215
I'd do anything for my family.

00:35:55.215 --> 00:35:57.074
Stop it.

00:36:02.639 --> 00:36:05.649
You keep everything to yourself.
Blame everything on yourself.

00:36:06.552 --> 00:36:08.385
Can't you let go?

00:36:09.314 --> 00:36:11.471
The one who hasn't moved on...

00:36:12.382 --> 00:36:14.474
is you, Jun.

00:36:17.473 --> 00:36:20.894
How long are you going to act
like the sacrificial victim?

00:36:20.894 --> 00:36:22.825
I'm sick of it!

00:36:31.090 --> 00:36:33.377
Let's just be happy together.

00:36:34.806 --> 00:36:36.438
Please.

00:36:37.076 --> 00:36:38.940
You have to move on.

00:36:47.880 --> 00:36:50.411
You don't have to hire me.

00:36:51.597 --> 00:36:53.648
Let's enjoy our lives.

00:36:57.578 --> 00:36:59.461
But I did this.

00:36:59.461 --> 00:37:01.912
You didn't do anything wrong.

00:37:03.956 --> 00:37:08.989
Please stop blaming yourself.

00:37:38.995 --> 00:37:41.967
Do you know why he is bruised all over?

00:37:44.322 --> 00:37:46.033
No.

00:37:46.941 --> 00:37:51.404
He was likely punished
over a long period of time.

00:38:03.736 --> 00:38:06.095
His ankles were also very swollen.

00:38:07.100 --> 00:38:09.840
I can't believe he ran
until his legs gave out.

00:38:11.267 --> 00:38:13.510
Why did you simply leave him be?

00:38:58.658 --> 00:39:01.738
[Banzai Baseball]

00:39:02.475 --> 00:39:03.946
I knew you'd check it out.

00:39:03.946 --> 00:39:05.899
Oh, well...

00:39:05.899 --> 00:39:07.854
What do you mean, you knew?

00:39:07.854 --> 00:39:10.117
I'm simply looking for talented people.

00:39:10.117 --> 00:39:11.969
I know.

00:39:13.060 --> 00:39:14.854
What are you smirking about?

00:39:14.854 --> 00:39:16.515
Oh, nothing.

00:39:18.622 --> 00:39:20.827
So, who are we picking?

00:39:24.423 --> 00:39:26.147
Great question.

00:39:32.065 --> 00:39:33.930
Come on in.

00:39:33.930 --> 00:39:35.691
Excuse me.

00:39:54.847 --> 00:39:56.455
What's up?

00:39:58.059 --> 00:40:01.605
I needed someone else
to bad-mouth him to.

00:40:01.605 --> 00:40:03.281
I see.

00:40:03.281 --> 00:40:07.575
I certainly know that stubborn fella well.

00:40:07.575 --> 00:40:08.951
Which one do you want?

00:40:08.951 --> 00:40:10.856
I'll have this one.

00:40:10.856 --> 00:40:12.686
- Thank you.
- Sure.

00:40:18.850 --> 00:40:22.750
I guess I'm still being swung around by him.

00:40:22.750 --> 00:40:24.206
Not that I entirely mind, though.

00:40:26.942 --> 00:40:31.529
Sawako, were you and my brother
not honest enough with each other?

00:40:32.470 --> 00:40:35.079
You don't have to worry about us anymore.

00:40:39.698 --> 00:40:42.310
Though I'm able to be a stranger,

00:40:42.310 --> 00:40:45.187
it's different between siblings, isn't it?

00:40:48.380 --> 00:40:50.563
I told him everything.

00:40:51.718 --> 00:40:53.528
For my own sake.

00:40:55.752 --> 00:40:57.783
That's for the better.

00:41:01.268 --> 00:41:05.184
You and I both need to become happy.

00:41:05.184 --> 00:41:08.577
Otherwise, he'll be disheartened forever.

00:41:13.100 --> 00:41:15.993
The two of us have been through a lot.

00:41:17.085 --> 00:41:21.306
But let's laugh. Good fortune
comes to those who laugh, right?

00:41:22.702 --> 00:41:24.184
Right.

00:41:29.855 --> 00:41:31.917
One moment.

00:41:35.219 --> 00:41:37.211
Hello?

00:41:37.211 --> 00:41:41.101
Good afternoon.
This is Risa Makita, from the Dreams.

00:41:41.991 --> 00:41:43.270
Hello there.

00:41:44.027 --> 00:41:46.653
Akito Sakurazaki.

00:41:46.653 --> 00:41:48.913
You are hired.

00:41:48.913 --> 00:41:51.803
What? Really?

00:41:53.214 --> 00:41:54.751
Thank you!

00:41:54.751 --> 00:41:56.885
Congratulations.

00:41:56.885 --> 00:41:58.897
When can you start working?

00:41:59.635 --> 00:42:01.643
Anytime!

00:42:01.643 --> 00:42:04.833
Then I'll see you at the office tomorrow.

00:42:05.467 --> 00:42:07.250
Thank you!

00:42:07.250 --> 00:42:09.379
Thank you!

00:42:09.379 --> 00:42:11.138
Have a good day!

00:42:13.961 --> 00:42:15.719
Was that...

00:42:16.373 --> 00:42:17.886
Yeah!

00:42:17.886 --> 00:42:19.515
Yes!

00:42:19.515 --> 00:42:22.517
Congrats! Good fortune did come!

00:42:24.214 --> 00:42:27.981
Stubborn as he may be, that guy...

00:42:28.845 --> 00:42:31.359
He never betrays anyone.

00:42:33.098 --> 00:42:34.504
Yeah.

00:42:53.343 --> 00:42:56.678
[General Manager]

00:42:56.678 --> 00:43:00.578
[Utilizing Sabermetrics - Akito Sakurazaki]

00:43:03.345 --> 00:43:05.227
Due to a change in assessment criteria,

00:43:05.227 --> 00:43:10.860
we are joined by the coaches this year
for our annual salary negotiations.

00:43:12.726 --> 00:43:16.551
Sakurazaki will take the floor from here.

00:43:16.551 --> 00:43:17.922
Yes, sir.

00:43:19.332 --> 00:43:21.103
- Huh?
- Sakurazaki?

00:43:21.103 --> 00:43:22.682
But...

00:43:22.682 --> 00:43:24.938
He's our newcomer.

00:43:25.931 --> 00:43:28.084
He's the younger brother of the GM.

00:43:28.084 --> 00:43:29.251
Yes.

00:43:32.181 --> 00:43:35.574
I'm Akito Sakurazaki.
It's nice to meet you all.

00:43:37.116 --> 00:43:39.741
The Dreams have negotiated annual salaries

00:43:39.741 --> 00:43:42.353
on the basis of a seniority system,

00:43:42.353 --> 00:43:47.966
which gave more to older players,
regardless of their skill.

00:43:47.966 --> 00:43:51.096
As a result,
skilled athletes were earning less,

00:43:51.096 --> 00:43:54.205
and promising young players
have had to be let go.

00:43:54.205 --> 00:43:58.526
See? He's got you there, Inamura.

00:43:58.526 --> 00:44:02.365
I won't deny it.
We do treat our older players favorably.

00:44:02.365 --> 00:44:07.221
They are the face of our team.
The veterans keep our dugout unified.

00:44:07.221 --> 00:44:09.577
Do you get what that means?

00:44:09.577 --> 00:44:14.771
He's never played baseball. I doubt he would.

00:44:14.771 --> 00:44:16.548
- Sirs.
- Sirs.

00:44:18.243 --> 00:44:22.024
Look to the future, not the past.

00:44:22.024 --> 00:44:24.585
He is a good analyst.

00:44:30.572 --> 00:44:31.913
Let's hear it.

00:44:33.822 --> 00:44:35.233
Continue.

00:44:36.078 --> 00:44:37.335
Yes, sir.

00:44:39.192 --> 00:44:41.996
Therefore, in order to avoid
losing any more players,

00:44:41.996 --> 00:44:44.484
we will change our evaluation metrics.

00:44:45.643 --> 00:44:48.008
Specifically,

00:44:48.008 --> 00:44:52.042
we will be referring to WAR,
and Clubhouse Values.

00:44:53.291 --> 00:44:59.183
WAR is about quantifying
how much a player contributes to victory.

00:44:59.183 --> 00:45:00.854
On the other hand,

00:45:00.854 --> 00:45:04.700
Clubhouse Values refers to traits
that are harder to quantify,

00:45:04.700 --> 00:45:08.225
like team cohesion, and leadership skills.

00:45:09.275 --> 00:45:11.852
Implementing this new metric

00:45:11.852 --> 00:45:17.718
will allow us to fairly evaluate
both younger players, and veterans alike.

00:45:17.718 --> 00:45:21.915
The salaries of our veterans
will certainly decrease.

00:45:22.859 --> 00:45:24.324
However, if we implement this system,

00:45:24.324 --> 00:45:27.083
we can renew our contracts
with every player this year.

00:45:27.083 --> 00:45:31.082
Negotiating with the veterans
will prove somewhat difficult.

00:45:31.082 --> 00:45:34.080
As such, Miyahara and I will handle those.

00:45:34.080 --> 00:45:37.567
Yes! We'll have them agreeing in no time.

00:45:37.567 --> 00:45:39.514
I'm absolutely raring to go!

00:45:39.514 --> 00:45:42.299
He may not be reliable,
but he can handle negotiations.

00:45:42.299 --> 00:45:46.139
No, I'm ready. I've got this.

00:45:46.139 --> 00:45:49.176
Will you be able to convince our veterans?

00:45:49.176 --> 00:45:50.615
I will!

00:45:50.615 --> 00:45:51.977
Yes, we will.

00:45:53.602 --> 00:45:57.369
Our veterans love the team.

00:45:57.369 --> 00:46:00.289
Keep all their teammates signed on,

00:46:00.289 --> 00:46:03.111
and they should consider the pay cut.

00:46:03.111 --> 00:46:04.878
Is that what you're getting at?

00:46:05.642 --> 00:46:06.976
Yes, sir.

00:46:07.768 --> 00:46:11.121
You're unexpectedly shrewd, aren't you?

00:46:13.567 --> 00:46:16.889
I have no objections.

00:46:19.920 --> 00:46:24.872
Then we will begin negotiations
using this new evaluation system.

00:46:25.561 --> 00:46:27.246
- Alright.
- Thank you again.

00:46:27.246 --> 00:46:28.872
Thank you.

00:46:33.058 --> 00:46:34.661
Yes!

00:46:53.440 --> 00:46:55.833
So? We can disband the team?

00:46:55.833 --> 00:46:59.937
Sir, the dissolution of a team
is unprecedented in Japanese baseball.

00:46:59.937 --> 00:47:01.916
Unprecedented?

00:47:01.916 --> 00:47:04.918
I've spent my whole life
doing the unprecedented.

00:47:04.918 --> 00:47:06.601
That is why I'm a success.

00:47:06.601 --> 00:47:09.698
That is why Yaoshima exists. Am I wrong?

00:47:13.723 --> 00:47:18.714
What do you think is the best way
to accomplish something unprecedented?

00:47:20.378 --> 00:47:25.460
I am not qualified to answer, sir.

00:47:25.460 --> 00:47:29.491
I will offer a famous saying instead.

00:47:30.973 --> 00:47:34.446
"Rome wasn't built in a day".

00:47:34.446 --> 00:47:38.395
To accomplish an unprecedented feat,

00:47:38.395 --> 00:47:41.970
you must take it one step at a time.

00:47:53.314 --> 00:47:57.194
Tell him to come to my office.

00:48:02.613 --> 00:48:04.107
Come in.

00:48:04.107 --> 00:48:05.439
Excuse me.

00:48:19.616 --> 00:48:23.668
How much was the team offered
to divide amongst their players last year?

00:48:25.848 --> 00:48:30.916
2.902 billion yen, sir.

00:48:30.916 --> 00:48:33.179
Do you think that's too little?

00:48:33.870 --> 00:48:36.635
Yes. Quite so.

00:48:38.930 --> 00:48:45.360
Goodness, what a shame.

00:48:47.833 --> 00:48:52.121
The team is in for a budget cut.

00:49:03.482 --> 00:49:05.810
Romanée-Contini.

00:49:05.810 --> 00:49:07.489
You're no wine expert, are you?

00:49:07.489 --> 00:49:09.576
Not at all.

00:49:11.363 --> 00:49:13.387
A wine lover will be joining us.

00:49:13.387 --> 00:49:14.528
Who?

00:49:14.528 --> 00:49:17.507
Wait, and you'll find out.

00:49:20.913 --> 00:49:22.833
What's this?

00:49:22.833 --> 00:49:25.730
It's your assigned annual salary.

00:49:25.730 --> 00:49:27.668
What?

00:49:27.668 --> 00:49:28.823
How...

00:49:28.823 --> 00:49:30.362
I stole the data.

00:49:30.362 --> 00:49:31.745
Obviously, I stole it.

00:49:31.745 --> 00:49:34.163
That's definitely not allowed.

00:49:34.163 --> 00:49:36.576
Whoever wants the data, lookie here!

00:49:37.308 --> 00:49:38.699
Ouch...

00:49:38.699 --> 00:49:40.203
I'll pass.

00:49:40.203 --> 00:49:41.684
If you'll excuse me.

00:49:44.049 --> 00:49:48.823
Hey, hey.

00:49:49.757 --> 00:49:53.012
Listen to what I've got to say.

00:49:53.012 --> 00:49:55.479
Don't be so on edge.

00:49:55.479 --> 00:49:58.017
Come, sit.

00:49:58.017 --> 00:50:03.243
Just give him five minutes, please.

00:50:04.606 --> 00:50:06.147
Sir.

00:50:07.572 --> 00:50:11.803
The thing is, I started an agency of my own.

00:50:13.183 --> 00:50:16.108
You can leave the salary negotiating to me.

00:50:16.108 --> 00:50:17.466
Sir.

00:50:17.466 --> 00:50:21.227
I'm a young player.
You won't make a buck off me.

00:50:21.227 --> 00:50:23.697
Treat me to a drink, and we'll call it even.

00:50:23.697 --> 00:50:26.534
You younger guys are paid too little.

00:50:26.534 --> 00:50:30.011
Number 31, Yuto Nara.

00:50:30.011 --> 00:50:33.562
Mr. Kurokawa's giving you an opportunity.

00:50:33.562 --> 00:50:36.445
You really ought to take it.

00:50:36.445 --> 00:50:39.439
Kato, Shirasaki, and Nojima
all signed with me.

00:50:39.439 --> 00:50:42.569
That's this season's whole starting line-up.

00:50:42.569 --> 00:50:46.967
Don't take the deal, and it's your loss.

00:50:49.481 --> 00:50:54.283
I know these Dreams contracts
like the back of my hand.

00:50:54.283 --> 00:50:56.932
Nara, join the group.

00:51:01.163 --> 00:51:03.404
Are you surprised?

00:51:03.404 --> 00:51:06.376
That's not like you.

00:51:06.376 --> 00:51:11.287
Is a 30% cut really all that difficult?

00:51:12.844 --> 00:51:13.772
It's impossible.

00:51:13.772 --> 00:51:15.966
Still...

00:51:15.966 --> 00:51:23.972
Negotiating with the players
is one of your jobs.

00:51:23.972 --> 00:51:25.771
Right?

00:51:30.689 --> 00:51:32.428
We'll take a 10% cut.

00:51:32.428 --> 00:51:33.452
30%.

00:51:33.452 --> 00:51:35.111
Then 15%.

00:51:36.361 --> 00:51:38.704
Are you haggling with me?

00:51:38.704 --> 00:51:41.113
You're the one driving us for a bargain, sir.

00:51:43.201 --> 00:51:47.094
Please explain to me
why a budget cut is necessary.

00:51:47.094 --> 00:51:51.665
Fine, explain I shall.

00:51:53.822 --> 00:51:55.445
The reason is simple.

00:51:55.445 --> 00:51:57.312
This team sucks at baseball!

00:51:57.312 --> 00:52:00.051
They're so bad, it's a waste of money!

00:52:00.051 --> 00:52:04.335
Every year, they're last.
Every year, they're in the red!

00:52:09.813 --> 00:52:15.515
Need I convince you any further?

00:52:17.556 --> 00:52:20.998
We're signing players on
at their lowest salary already.

00:52:25.796 --> 00:52:30.837
I cannot accept a 30% cut to our budget.

00:52:32.837 --> 00:52:38.742
Well, well. It seems you weren't listening.

00:52:40.437 --> 00:52:44.797
I am not speaking my mind here.

00:52:45.625 --> 00:52:49.441
I am giving you an order, as the team owner.